segments.text: Can you discuss the time that you spent in Vietnam?
Well, okay, in 65, I went over to the advisor.
I served with the unit that was very poorly trained.
There were three of us Americans.
There was an officer.
There was two non-commissioned officers from America, and there was one Australian officer.
And we advised this infantry battalion.
We were in an area that was very critical in defense of the Vietnamese army and of the territory.
We were in the Quang Ngai area, up in the I Corps, up where Da Nang and Tam Kee and all those places are.
And that was in what you call a tribe country of Vietnamese, Laos, and Cambodian they met.
So we conducted operations around it.
But remember that some of these Vietnamese officers were sympathizers with the Viet Cong.
And so therefore, they wouldn't fight against their own brother and cousin, just like any horse else.

uh it's pretty rough for us to live pretty rough for us to live with those people and advise them and then it was even rougher tough for us to be with them because we'd never know when they're putting us out and we'd be killed when we go out in operation
We had to live, sleep with them, and everything.
We had to follow their costumes.
I went to church with some of them.
I went to Catholic Mass with them on Sundays.
I ate their food.
I spoke their language.
I visited their villages.
I visited their relatives.
And I look on in on myself.
So therefore, you know, I had it made in a way, you know, and I was real slim in those days.
They were confused.
They didn't know if I was a Hawaiian or Filipino or what.
And at one time I told them I was a war orphan.
And so they believed it.
But I stayed there and I attended the Bob Hope Prison Show in 1965.
And then in 1966, I was wounded.
I stepped on a landmine.
I was paralyzed on the way down.
I was declared never to walk again.
And then that team that I was with was overrun and completely demolished.
None of those people are alive now.
And I landed in the hospital in the Philippines.
I was in Clark Air Force Base.
and I was paralyzed.
I was declared never to walk again.
But I did it.
Thank God, you know, I was a paratrooper, and I was a gun-holed airborne ranger and everything.
And I had faith, and I wanted to walk.
So I did.
After 10 months of struggling, kneeling and dragging myself and getting up to a wall,
I walked, and I walked out of the hospital.
And then I went back to Fort Brand, North Carolina, and I went back to jump status, and I made three faster jumps in one day.
My wife thought I was crazy.
She was going to divorce me and everything.
She thought, you know, a bug done hit my mind.
She didn't think I was all there.
And I went with Special Forces, and I started training with Special Forces.
Then it was known as the Green Berets.
In 1962, the late President Kennedy, of course, he observed the training of the special forces.
And Vietnam was developed and developed.
And of course, Korean classic just came about in the Dominican Republic.
And the President thought that

his advisors, as I understand the story goes, that this was a sort of, I don't know what they called that, counter guerrilla warfare tactic, that we'd have to be trained and you'd have to have special people in this qualification for training.
counterinsurgency and guerrilla warfare tactics and all.
So then he thought about the Special Forces.
And so President Kennedy said, hey look, what about these Special Forces people?
Let's have them be identified as the Green Berets.
And that's
Let's let the public know that we have special people trained for the counterinsurgency tactic.
So then he authorized us to wear the Green Beret.
And then he said that the Green Beret was a symbol of excellence, mark of distinction, badge of courage, and fight for freedom.
So then we proved it to the world and to every country that we were assigned to.
that we are instructors, we're teachers to their militia, to their military.
We're linguists, we're trained.
Someone said that we were a special breed of men.
Special forces are a special breed of men.
We train in our way to train others.
to learn the meaning of freedom.
And we train them.
We know weaponry.
We know operational intelligence, which includes meteorology, fingerprinting, interpretation of photography, interrogation for linguists.
We know medical training.
Some of the medics are trained almost like doctors.
We're trained in communications.
We can communicate all around the world in Morse codes and in engineering.
We can build, destroy.
We're trained in light and heavy weapons.
We know every weapon in the system.
from the BB gun to the 105 holster.
We can operate any weapon, and we can not destroy, but we can disassemble and assemble any weapon.
And some of these fellows can assemble them blindfolded.
That's amazing.
So that's what a special force can do.
So, in 1968, then I went back again with Special Forces and I was assigned to an operation intelligence team to gather intelligence information of the enemy.
I was trained
I didn't have a weapon.
I know all about all the weapons that I just mentioned.
I guess one thing, it was hard to tell who the enemy was, wasn't it?
Well, in a way, for the other conventional soldiers, remember the Special Forces are unconventional.
We live out there with them.
The conventional soldiers are these other soldiers that stayed together.
Being here in South Vietnam and North Vietnam, all of them looked alike.
Well, that's where the intelligence came in.
But you're right.
We didn't know.
I had a long story.
You hear all kinds of stories.
I had a couple of boys I went to high school with served over there.
And they said that even the young children
at times could be your enemy.
A little kid would come up and throw a hand in the air.
You never know who your enemy was.
But they were wonderful people.
And they were confused as we were.
They were just more confused than we were.
Because they wanted liberty.
They wanted freedom.
But yet their own brothers would not give it to them.
Their own
their own cousins that were in office.
I'm sorry that that pencil went down.
It's not going down.
Do you think the Soviets had a lot, were behind a lot of it?
I think that in some way they had some influence, yeah.
They did, just like they have in Cuba.
Just like they have in Central America.
Have you ever stopped to think
And why there's no Hispanic in Saskatoon Central America?
Is it an advisory?
No, I never thought about that.
You know the news?
They talk about Army advisors, right?
But they never talk about a Hispanic in the Army being an advisor.
Why is it?
Come to think about it.
How long did you stay in Vietnam?
Well, the first time, I stayed five months, almost six.
I was wounded.
And the second time, in 1968, I stayed almost four months.
Is this the time when you saved the other men?
And the second time in 1968, yes.
That was the time that I volunteered for this mission.
May 2nd, 1968.
And this was the time that you eventually got the Congressional Medal of Honor, is that right?
Well, I was recommended for the medal then.
My commander didn't know the full extent of the operation.
And, of course, it was so...
Excuse me, it was so...
The mission was so classified that I didn't even know about that.
I didn't know the full extent because those men that were asking for assistance, they were denied assistance.
That's how classified the mission was.
There was no helicopter going in there once they let them in until after the operation.

But since I was in a different launch area, launch side area, I went up with my helicopter and I asked the forward air controller, had been an assistant to us, an assistant to us, and he said that, you know, that we,
that he was at loss because he couldn't support any information.
He couldn't support any information because there was a secret operation mission.
However, he pinpointed an area where we could get to, knowing that these people were in desire of help, in desire of need of help.
You know, you just can't neglect your brother.
And I'm glad that that person acknowledged his location.
However, I can't find him.
I don't know him.
And maybe he wants it that way.
There's others that have changed their name that don't want to be located because of a sacred mission operation.
But I'm glad that I that
I was able, it could have been anyone else.
A lot of people asked me, why did I do it?
You know, I couldn't, those people could have done the same for me.
I knew some of the men.
In fact, I just got a letter from one of them.
It was a pretty tough day.
It was a day that you can honestly say that you earned your money.
It was very sad.
One of the hardest things for a recipient of the Medal of Honor is to know that you wear the medal and you're able to talk about your experience.
That's when I wondered if it was really maybe too painful to talk about, you know.
Well, in a way it is, you know, but in a way the public has to know.
Because the public has to know.
I tell you what, cut that off.
When were you first nominated or brought up to get the Congressional Medal of Honor?
Well, 1968.
after the action of May 2nd.
And I didn't know.
I didn't have any knowledge of it.
I was wounded.
I came through hospitals.
I came through two hospitals in Vietnam and Japan and the United States.
I received a nation's second highest award.
It was an interim award, but no one knew about it.
My commander didn't even know that I was alive.
What is the second highest honor?
The nation's second highest award is Distinguished Service Prize.
And I wore that for seven years, for five years.
And other people, other servicemen that remember me,
that served in Vietnam and that served with special forces, they questioned me about the Medal of Honor.
I had no knowledge of it.
And my commander, who didn't think that I was still alive, had recommended me for the Medal of Honor, but had given me an interim award of the Distinguished Service Corps.
He had made a recommendation for the Medal of Honor.
which I have documentation.
And that went on until 1973, 74.
And then I found out the full extent of the opera, of the recommendation, everything.
And I...
It still took how many years before you got it?
Thirteen.
Thirteen years.
That's a long time.
It is.
It was.
And there was a lot of frustration.
But, you know, in the military, the military is one big family.
And thank God you have so many people that help you, you know, that take so much interest in you.
I have some of the greatest friends that I have met.
My wife and I and the kids.
that these people would have never rested until they saw that justice was done.
Would you have to say that that's one of the proudest days of your life, when the president gave you that medal?
Well, yes, because the president recognized me.
Or because the president, what he says in that tape about the Vietnam veterans.
Because that was really the first praise that the Vietnam veterans had ever gotten, really?
I think, yes.
From the government or the public or anybody?
But still, we have to think that we have the POW and MIA and the Agent Andre.
I have spoken with the president after he gave me the award and later.
There's one of the highlights of mine.
career or the lifetime in my career.
But I keep thinking my buddies, they're still behind the bamboo curtain.
And their children, which I have letters, I receive letters from.
You work a lot with the MIA and POW cause?
I do, I do.
I'm very deeply involved with it.
I'm religiously involved with it.
and any of the veterans that are wounded, I try to help as much as I can.
In fact, sometimes I even ask my wife if she thinks that she's neglected by the children because of my travel.
What about the Agent Orange controversy?
Do you have any feelings about that?
Well, yes, I think I'm going to make them obey Agent Orange.
I flew a lot with those range hands, with the foliation planes.
It was made, the veterans, the victims of the Asian War were given an option of accepting 180 million dollars.
And to me, this was an insult.
In fact, I went to Houston to testify before the federal judge because we took an oath to defend this country, and this country didn't set a price tag.
Yet, they're setting a price tag for us after we defend this country.
They're saying, hey, look, we're giving you 180 million bucks because we think that, or you think that you was injured
Because there's defoliation.
These lawyers that have these people that are injured in car accidents get millions of dollars.
That's right.
Well, that goes back to what I said earlier.
Way back in the day.
These people have too much education to have enough common sense.
I mean, they are the ones that are enjoying freedom at the expense of our body's life.
So...
By taking our soldiers and defending these other countries, it's keeping them from having the people invade our country where we don't have to see the war sites.
We will never have this country, ma'am.
We will never have this country invaded.
You know why?
No.
Because this country has got too much pride.
This country has got too much self-respect.
Yet, these people...
that are upholding us to keep the self-respect in this prime, they're lowering this country.
And they're the ones that are getting these other people to fight against them.
Those are the ones that are doing it.
The monetarys are strong.
You'd be surprised how many people, once they know that you're an American, they would love to talk to you, to touch you.
Because you come from a free world.
This country is the freest of all.
Yet those people in the Pentagon, in those high-level offices, they're the ones that are destroying us, not us.
And that's why I have been to Congress.
And I have asked them to leave that jungle of air-conditioned offices to come down here.

and see us they don't know how we live they make the rules and regulations up there they don't know what it is you know to go across the mud they don't they have forgotten but then who's going to suffer our children the future leaders of this country and who's going to make them suffer
Our own leader.
